{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393346966/1937111901/0324.xml":{"full_text":"Leading Bankers Are\nOut To Boom Business\nPolicies of Present Administration Are Given Some\nBlame for Recession\u2014Aldrich Speaks Before\nNew York Chamber of Commerce\nBy RONALD O. VAN TINE\n(United Pres* Staff Correspondent)\nNew York, Nov. 18\u2014(UP)\u2014Lead*\n(ng bonkers and industrialists, blam\ning the current business recession\non policies of the Roosevelt admin\nistration, advanced a \u201crepeal and\nmodlflcatldon\" program today, which\nthey claimed would bring recovery.\nTheir spokesman was Wlnthrop\nW. Aldrich, chairman of the board\not the Chase National bank, who de\nclared that \u201cif the existing laws\nwhich hamper business recovery\nshould be promptly repelaed or ade\nquately modified, the automatic re\nsult would be that industrial pro\nduction woifld Increase and that the\nexisting business depression would\nbe checked\u2014a result which would\nbenefit every member of the com\nmunity.\u201d\nAldrich demanded a return to the\ngold standard, a balanced budget,\nrepeal of the undistributed profits\ntax, modification of the capital\ngains tax and the freeing of pub\nlic utilities from government com\npetition. He declared that a bal\nanced budget was the chief factor,\nand that if the treasury reached\nthat goal, \"the cornerstone of the\nfoundation of true business recovery\nwill have been laid.\"\nMany Big Men Present\nAldrich addressed the 169th an\nnual dinner meeting of the New\nYork state Chamber of Commerce,\nof which he is president, and in the\naudience of 800 were:\nJohn D. Rockefeller, his brother\nin-law, and two of Rockefeller's sons,\nLawrence and Nelson; Charles R.\nGay, president of the New York stock\nexchange; Colby M. Chester, chair\nman of General Foods; Tom Glrd\nler, chairman of the Republic Steel\ncorporation; Thomas J. Watson,\npresident of the International Bus\niness Machine corporation and of\nthe International Chamber of Com\nmerce; Thomas L. Parkinson, presi\ndent ot the Equitable Life Insur\nance company; and many other\nbanking, industrial and business\nleaders.\nFirst Broad Statement\nHis address contained the first\nbroad statement ot the attitude of\nbusiness toward the administration\u2019s\npolicies since congress convened in\nextraordinary session last Monday.\nAldrich referred to suggestions\nemanating from Washington that\nrevision of the tax laws be limited to\nrelief for small corporations and\nemail businesses.\n\"If this suggestion should be fol\nlowed,\" he said, \"the attempt to\nencourage business would be un\nsuccessful. The practical question\nIs whether congress wishes to get\nresults.\n\"Both small businesses and big\nbusinesses are hampered by existing\nlegislation big business is In no\nway distinguishable from small bus\niness In terms of employment and\nthe creation of prosperity. After\nall, big business represents only the\nsum total of millions of wage earn\ners and stockholders.\"\nAgrees with President\nAldrich said he agreed with the\npresident that the fundamental sit\nuation today could not be compared\nto 1039; that the banking system\nwas not overly extended. Interest\nrates were low and speculation did\nnot overhang the markets.\n\"When, then,\" he asked, \"Is the\ncause of the business recession?\n\"I believe that the primary cause\nIs to be found In Important gov\nernmental policies, some of which\nalready bear heavily on business\nand others of which undermine\nconfidence In the future on the part\nof the Investing public and the bus\niness community. Many govern\nmental policies, moreover, create\nuncertainty, and uncertainty Is the\none thing above all others It is\nmost difficult for business to cope\nwith.\u201d\nBusiness Should Expand\nHe agreed that it was \"obvious\"\nthat everything possible should be\ndone through private enterprise to\nexpand business and Increase em\nployment, but Said that that accom\nplishment \"depends more on what Is\ndone In Washington in the near fu\nture than on anything else\" because\n\"private enterprise goes forward\nonly when the conditions are such\nthat confidence exists In the possi\nbility of conducting business on a\nprofitable basis.\"\nAldrich said there was Increasing\nevidence that the administration to\nday \u201chas assumed a more concilia\ntory and constructive attitude from\nthe standpoint of business and\nfinance than we have seen for a\nlong time.\" He \"welcomed\" the re\ncent assertion by Secretary of the\nTreasury Henry Morgenthau, Jr.,\nthat the budget would be balanced,\nand concluded:\nMore Is Needed\n\"But more Is needed. The undis\ntributed profits tax should be re\npealed. The capital gains tax\nshould be taken out of the Income\ntax category and fixed at a low\nflat rate so that men will be en\ncouraged to take profits, shift In\nvestments, set immobilized funds In\nmotion and take reasonable risks.\n\"The public utilities should be\nfreed from governmental competi\ntion In order that they may press\nvigorously forward In making up\ntheir vast arrears of construction\nand re-equipment. And the rail\nroads should be enoouraged to do\nUkewlM.\"\nCOAST DEFENSE\nUNDER DISCUSSION\nTechnical aspects of our coast de\nfenses were discussed by MaJ. Wil\nliam Hesketh, Instructor stationed\nat Bridgeport, last night at the\nmeelng of the Waterbury chapter,\nReserve Officers\u2019 associate, at the\npost office. Reports were made and\nMaJ. Newton W. Alexander told\nmembers that the Waterbury chap\nter now leads the state In member\nship. MaJ. Mortimer A. O\u2019Hara pre\nsided and It was voted to hold the\nm,xt meeting Dec. 16.\nARE WHAT WE CALL\nTHESE VALUES!\nPOSTER\nBEDS\nChoice of Finish\n50c a\nWeek!\nHandsomely styled to traditional\ncolonial lines, and in your choice of\nmaple, walnut, or mahogany fin\nishes! Tull or twin sise your\nchoice! At a dramatic reduction for\nFriday and Saturday only don't\nmiss It!\nOpen Friday and Saturday Until 9 P. M.\nBOSTON\nF URn ITU R\u20ac CO.\nnf.ee\nLast Treaty Ship\nFlog* and pennants, fluttering,\nthe U. 8. 8. Wichita, last of the\n18 heavy cruisers built for tho\nnavy under limitations of the\nLondon Treaty, floats on the Del\naware River after launching at\nthe Philadelphia Navy Yard.\nFraming the ship Is the steel\nwork of the traveling crane used\nIn Its construction.\nMANY CASES ARE\nHEARD YESTERDAY\nDeputy Motor Vehicle\nCommissioner Disposes\nof Law Violators\nCalled to a hearing before Dep\nuty Commissioner Francis W. Ho\ngan of the Motor Vehicle Depart\nment at city court yesterday, Thur\nman Walton, of 210 Bishop street\nand Anthony Lombard of 102\nBridge street were ordered to ap\npear for a future re-hearing as re\nsult of the commissioner\u2019s findings.\nThey were called for examination\nof motor vehicle records.\nHoward Whitmore Andrews, 80\nLinden street, charged with operat\ning under the influence of liquor,\ngranted limited license.\nJoseph Fisher, Jr., 14 Bridge\nstreet, oonvlcted of operating with\nout a license in 1838, given permis\nsion to take examination.\nAdolph Dublcki, 307 Washington\nstroet, convicted of operating with\nout a license and reckless driving,\ninstructed to have his employer ad\nvise the commissioner that he\nwishes Dublcki to drive. If such ac\ntion is taken, the board will con\nsider reinstatement.\nDecision reserved in the case of\nAlex Churchclow, of Terryvllle, ac\ncused but not convicted of operat\ning under influence of liquor.\nJohn Marek, Torrington, arraign\ned on a complaint of illegal regis\ntration, warned.\nFrank Sokolowskl, Marlon ave\nnue, Plantsvllle, ordered to obtain\nInsurance, after hearing on con\nviction of operating while under in\nfluence of liquor.\nSteve Bodwlk, of Sharon arraign\ned on charges of violating rules of\nroad, warned, and reinstated.\nIn the case of Halsey F. Web\nster, New Hartford, the commis\nsioner reserved decision.\nMelvin Francis Essex, 886 Wol\ncott street, Waterbury, reinstated\nand financial case closed. The case\nof Allen Curtis, of Taconlo simil\narly handled.\nThe remainder of the cases in\nvolved financial responsibility re\nquirements, and all were closed.\nThey were: Kenneth L. Sanford,\nWaterbury; Robert Ostrander, Tor\nrington: William J. Livingston\nWest Cornwall: Frank H. Lyons,\nTorrington; John Kazersky, Yales\nvllle and Edward S. Gray, Water\nbury.\nHARRY S. COE ON\nMEETING GROUP\nHarry S. Coe, of Waterbury, was\na member of the committee in\ncharge of the meeting last night at\nWestville at which Victor E. Luc\nchtni, of Meriden, was elected pres\nident o fthe New Haven County\nFarm Bureau; Edward P. Rowland,\nOxford, vice-president; Mrs. C. C.\nRogers, Wolcott, vice-president;\nHerbert Elker, Milford, secretary.\nOther members of the committee\nwere; J. Edward Coer, Southbury;\nMrs. W. 8. Kelloff, Derby; Benja\nmin P. Storrs, Cheshire; Paul M.\nWright, Orange; R. W. Young. North\nHaven. Increase in membership\nwas reported by W. W. Ham, Bran\nford, president, and Raymond K.\nClapp, former county agent, now\nmember of the staff of Connecti\ncut State College, served as toast\nmaster.\nDEFENDANT GETS\nCOURT'S VERDICT\nA verdict for the defendant *u\nreturned yesterday in superior court\nby a Jury in the case of Nora Arnold\nagainst the Harvey Shop. Inc., with\nJudge Edwin C. Dickenson presid\ning Damages of $7,800 were sought\nfor an alleged fall on steps In the\nSouth Main street store. W. P.\nWertheimer represented the plain\ntiff. Martin E. Oormfty, of New Ha\nven, the defendant.\n\u2022OPT FLOOR FOB COMFORT\nDon't iron for hours standing\non a hard floor. You'll to much\n\u25a0ore tired when the week's laun\ndry Is done than you would be it\nyou stood on a rubboi mat, or\nooa mad* of thick Unoleum.\n15x24 In. Rubber\nLINK DOOR MAT\nRubberised fab\nric link! and oil\ntempered spring\nwtro.\n79*\nMade from beat\n8 ply material.\nRust resistant.\nISIee IB x 14 In.\n|nuy now and\nsave at thla low\nprice!\nOVAL B